    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a bizarre, yet fundamental, phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same fate, no matter how far apart they are.  If you measure a property of one entangled particle, you instantly know the corresponding property of the other, even if it's across the galaxy.  The key difference from classical correlation is that in the quantum case, the properties aren't determined until the moment of measurement, which is where the spooky action at a distance comes in. Think of it like two magical, interconnected coins that only decide if they are heads or tails when one is flipped.",
      "source": "target",
