    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the coin thing makes sense but the 'spooky' part is what's tripping me up. why is it considered spooky instead of just being a weird rule of physics? like what actually makes it feel different from just two objects being connected?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"spooky\" aspect, as Einstein famously called it, stems from the *instantaneity* of the correlation, which seems to violate the speed limit of the universe—the speed of light. With classical correlations, like having two pre-set gloves in separate boxes, the correlation exists *before* you look. In entanglement, the particles genuinely do not have a definite state until the measurement happens, and that measurement instantaneously influences the state of its partner. It's not just a pre-arranged signal; it's a shared, indeterminate reality collapsing together.",
      "source": "target",
